Explanation:

We use a loop that iterates from the highest bit set (start) to the lowest bit set (end). In each iteration, we update i by XORing it with i >> 1 to flip the least significant bit. This ensures that we only iterate over the required range and generate valid n-bit gray code numbers. The solution has a high efficiency since the time complexity is O(log(n)) due to the iterative approach, and the space complexity is O(1) as we only use a constant amount of space to store the generated numbers. The energy implications are low as the solution does not involve any resource-consuming operations.

